<TITLE> Tk 4900 crore projects taken to develop telecoms: minister </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, May 6 (bdnews24.com)The government has commissioned projects worth Tk 4,900 crore to develop telecommunications sector including a Tk 2,000 crore project to expand state-run Teletalk network, the telecoms minister said on Wednesday. The projects have been taken to build a 'digital Bangladesh' as promised by prime minister Sheikh Hasina, Raziuddin Ahmed Razu told reporters on his return from 4th World Telecommunication Policy Forum at Portugal's capital Lisbon. The minister said at the media briefing that the process of installing a national IP backbone had been finalised. WiMAX technology was being tested and the process of introducing third-generation mobile phone technology was going on, Razu added. "We hope to turn a new page on information technology by implementing internet information network expansion project." He said mobile-phone network will be introduced in 11 Upazila of the hills region on May 14 by the prime minister from Lama of Bandarban. The projects include Tk 200 crore for IT, Tk 600 crore for WiMAX, Tk 1500 crore for setting up next generation networking and optical fibre on easy loan from Japan International Cooperation Agency. The work of these projects will end by 2011-12, said Md Khabiruzzaman, managing director of Bangladesh Telecommunications Company Ltd (BTCL). There is a proposal to cut internet fees to Tk 300, said Zia Ahmed, chairman of telecoms regulator Bangladesh Telecommunication Regulatory Commission (BTRC). BTCL and BSCCL will be merged and Teletalk will remain as a subsidiary company, he added. bd
